title: WTB: 1889 A35 Goodwin Album Page Cards
author: RFResnick

posts.post_title: WTB: 1889 A35 Goodwin Album Page Cards
posts.post_content:
This is my first WTB post, so please pardon any rookie mistakes.

I'm interested in buying A35 Goodwin Album pages/cards, in this order of preference:

1. Mickey Welch, John Ward, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe
2. John Ward
3. Jim Mutrie, Ledell Titcomb, Art Whitney, and a child mascot
4. Elmer Foster, William Brown, Bill George, Mike Tiernan
5. Mike Slattery, Pat Murphy, Ed Crane, Gil Hatfield

(As you might guess from the names above, I've been focusing on 19th century New York Giants lately.) 

If you have any to sell, I'm happy to discuss any of these cards in virtually any condition. If you have any leads, I'm all ears! Please send me a PM or email at [url]RFResnick@aol.com[/url]. Thanks in advance. -- Rick

**crickets**

BUMPING though it seems like A35s aren't a popular subject. LOL.

Anyone? Bueller? Bueller?

I'd appreciate any leads on the A35s I listed. Thanks. -- Rick

Personally I think these are hugely under valued so I'm sitting on mine and waiting for a time when PSA/SGC/BVG comes up with a larger holder.  If you can slab these pages... My guess is the prices will go up 3-5x current values.  I have 4 Cap Anson pages and feel like these are ridiculously low for such a rare item.  The lithography is AMAZING on these cards.  5yrs ago T205s were the the little brother to the T206 set... Have you seen some of the prices for high end T205 cards lately.... in some cases out pacing Big Brother T206 cards.  A35 album pages will have their day!!!!

I can never get enough of the following thread:

[url]https://www.net54baseball.com/showthread.php?t=285910&highlight=rounds[/url]

To me, this is one of the most beautiful baseball memorabilia projects I've seen out there.  I know a lot of people have reviewed this thread but if I ever see a post about A35's I'm probably going to add a link to the above thread because it's just that cool.  

Good luck with the A35 search.

I have a set of rounds and i agree, just beautiful cards!! Way undervalued. As are all of the “card albums” as well, but the A35’s are rarer and even nicer. 

Like the M101-1s, grading would help the prices dramatically.
